com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.manager

Class EMXClient

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.manager.EMXClient
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    DemoIFAClient, DemoProviderClient

    public class EMXClient
extends Object
    EMXClient is the EMX Integrator's engine class that connects to EMX, manages the session protocol, signs and sends EMXMessages and directs received messages to user-definable handlers.

    Application developers who are using the EMXClient (i.e. those who are not using the CameronFIX UniversalServer) will need to subclass and extend EMXClient. Many of EMXClient's methods do nothing and are provided as hooks through which a subclass can add its required functionality. The developer needs to implement whichever of the message handlers are required for processing the EMXMessages that the application needs to handle. Methods not needed can be left unimplemented.

    The handler methods are:

    • viewLogonResponse(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage)
    • logReceivedEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
    • logSentEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
    • handleOINPMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.OINPMessage)
    • handleTBKDMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TBKDMessage)
    • handleECNIMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.ECNIMessage)
    • handleECNPMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.ECNPMessage)
    • handleCSMHMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMHMessage)
    • handleCSMDMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMDMessage)
    • handleCSMAMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMAMessage)
    • handleVREQMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.VREQMessage)
    • handleVRESMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.VRESMessage)
    • handleTREQMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TREQMessage)
    • handleTRESMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TRESMessage)
    • handleMACKMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.MACKMessage)
    • handleMERRMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.MERRMessage)
    • handleOtherEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
    • handleFIXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage)
    • updateConversationID(int, int, java.lang.String, long)
    • handleCertificateNotFound(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage, java.lang.String, java.lang.String, java.math.BigInteger)
    • handleVerifyFailure(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage, java.lang.String, java.security.cert.X509Certificate)
    Only those handlers actually required need be implemented.

    Messages can be sent by calling the following methods, either from one of the handler methods or, if originating a new message, from another thread:

    • sendEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
    • returnMERRMessage(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
    • logout()

    Please read the documentation for the EMXClient constructor, EMXClient(), which describes how the starting FIX sequence numbers can be specified if the need arises.

    Author:
    Christopher J Burton, 04/Dec/2001.

    • Constructor Detail

      • EMXClient

        public EMXClient()
        Constructs an EMXClient that is capable of connecting to an EMX Hub. Apart from the action noted below, the constructor performs no action other than to create an EMXClient object. This constructor will be called (through chaining) automatically by any subclass's constructor.

        The constructor checks the system properties to see if alternative starting sequence numbers have been specified. These will be applied to the first logon only. Following that, the sequence numbers that the persistence mechanism determines will be used.

        To override the starting sequence numbers that the persistence mechanism would have used, specify the Java command line option "-DoutMsgSeqNum=p", to set the first outgoing sequence number to p, and/or "-DinMsgSeqNum=q" to set the first expected incoming sequence number to q.

        The facility to change first sequence numbers is not required under normal conditions, but EMX's compliance tests require it to be used.

    • Method Detail

      • setProperties

        public final void setProperties(Properties properties)
        Specifies the Properties that the EMXClient requires. Either this method or individual "set" methods may be used. If the specified Properties contains any errors, a description of the error is written to System.err and the program exits immediately without returning.

        Property names that may be passed in the Properties object are:

        • CompID - The Partcipant ID (SenderCompID) that the application will use.
        • hostname - The host name of the hub system.
        • hostport - The port number of the hub system.
        • keystore - The keystore file name.
        • truststore - The truststore file name.
        • keystorePassword - The keystore password. The keystore password is taken to be "password" if not supplied.
        • keyPassword - The key password. The key password is taken to be the same as the keystore password if not supplied.
        • verify - The verification policy (default NONE). See setVerify(String) for the possible options and their meanings.
        • StartTime - The time that the EMXClient should first attempt to log on to EMX each day, default 08:00.
        • heartbeat - The heartbeat interval that is to be used for the session. Default is 60 seconds.
        Parameters:
        properties - The properties that are to be assigned to this EMXClient.

      • setVerify

        public final void setVerify(int verify)
        Defines whether received EMX messages should be verified against our truststore or not. Default, if this method is not called, is no verification.

        The verification policy may be specified via the Properties that are supplied to the setProperties() method. The options that can be passed to this method are:

        • VERIFY_NONE: No incoming messages will be verified;
        • VERIFY_PARTICIPANTS: Messages signed by other participants will be verified;
        • VERIFY_ALL: All messages, including MACKs and MERRs from the EMX Hub and messages signed by EMX Services, will be verified.
        Parameters:
        verify - the verification level

      • setVerify

        public final void setVerify(String verify)
        Defines whether received EMX messages should be verified against our truststore or not. Default, if this method is not called, is no verification.

        The verification policy may be specified via the Properties that are supplied to the setProperties() method. The options available to both this method and for specification via Properties are:

        • verify=NONE: No incoming messages will be verified;
        • verify=PARTICIPANTS: Messages signed by other participants will be verified;
        • verify=ALL: All messages, including MACKs and MERRs from the EMX Hub and messages signed by EMX Services, will be verified.
        Parameters:
        verify - the verification level

      • connect

        public final void connect()
                   throws InterruptedException
        Connects to the EMX Hub. Your application must already have defined the host and port of the EMX Hub to which you want to connect, and the EMX Participant ID (SenderCompID) that you are to use. These can be set with:
        • setHost(java.net.InetAddress, int)
        • setCompID(java.lang.String)
        or alternatively as part of a Properties collection, using:
        • setProperties(java.util.Properties)

        This method starts (or attempts to start) a session with the EMX Hub and does not return until the session has logged out or otherwise terminated. Application messages received during the session will be made available via calls to handler methods that application code can implement. The handler methods are:

        • viewLogonResponse(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage)
        • logReceivedEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
        • logSentEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
        • handleOINPMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.OINPMessage)
        • handleTBKDMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TBKDMessage)
        • handleECNIMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.ECNIMessage)
        • handleECNPMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.ECNPMessage)
        • handleCSMHMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMHMessage)
        • handleCSMDMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMDMessage)
        • handleCSMAMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.CSMAMessage)
        • handleVREQMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.VREQMessage)
        • handleVRESMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.VRESMessage)
        • handleTREQMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TREQMessage)
        • handleTRESMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.TRESMessage)
        • handleMACKMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.MACKMessage)
        • handleMERRMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.MERRMessage)
        • handleOtherEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
        • handleFIXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage)
        • updateConversationID(int, int, java.lang.String, long)
        • handleCertificateNotFound(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage, java.lang.String, java.lang.String, java.math.BigInteger)
        • handleVerifyFailure(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage, java.lang.String, java.security.cert.X509Certificate)

        While the connection is active, messages can be sent by calling any of the following methods, either from one of the handler methods or, if originating a new message, from another thread:

        • sendEMXMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
        • returnMERRMessage(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, com.camerontec.catalys.server.adapter.emx.message.EMXMessage)
        • logout()
        Throws:
        IllegalStateException - If any of the required settings have not been made.
        InterruptedException - If the thread is interrupted while waiting for a connection to be made.

      • getNewPersister

        protected IFIXSessionStatePersister getNewPersister()
        A subclass needs to implement this method in order to provide a new instance of IPersister for each connection attempt. The implementation MUST NOT return the same object each time it is called. It MUST return a new instance on every call. This method replaces the deprecated setPersister method, which would only work if the IPersister was capable of being reused on subsequent connection attempts. We have found, in practice, that some IPersister implementations do not mind if called again after having been closed. But, in general, the IPersister API requires that a new IPersister object should be provided for each connection attempt.
        Returns:
        a new persister

      • returnMERRMessage

        public final void returnMERRMessage(String errorCode,
                                    String text,
                                    EMXMessage request)
                             throws MessageException,
                                    FatalProtocolException,
                                    IOException
        Deprecated. Use the alternative method with an integer code argument.
        Generates and sends a MERR message. The generated MERR message contains the supplied error code and text, and is addressed to the originator of the supplied request message.

        This method provides a simple and convenient means for a Fund Provider to send a MERR back to the sender when a received message cannot be processed.

        Parameters:
        errorCode - An EMX Error Code that indicates the type of the error.
        text - A description of the error, designed to help the originator in idenfifying and correcting the error (in a new attempt).
        request - The EMX message in which the application has found the error. This is required so that the correct return address for the MERR can be determined.
        Throws:
        MessageException - If the message format is bad, or it doesn't contain all of the required fields.
        FatalProtocolException - If the session is not (or is no longer) logged in.
        IOException - if the message cannot be sent

      • onConnectionTermination

        protected boolean onConnectionTermination(int terminationCode,
                                          int repeatCount)
        This method may be implemented by a subclass to define whether an automatic attempt at continuing the session should be made.

        If the return value is true, the EMXClient will attempt to reestablish the connection and continue the session, without returning from the connect() method.

        If the return value is false, the EMXClient will return from the connect() method.

        The default implementation, which the client may call after intercepting any situations that he wishes to handle differently, implements the following policy:

        • Stop immediately if the client has initiated a logout.
        • Stop immediately if we have presented a bad certificate or if our clock is not sufficiently well synchronised with EMX's.
        • Try for a maximum of 3 times if we cannot connect to EMX Hub for any other reason.
        • For any other problem, on the basis that the problem is likely to be transient or that, following diagnosis of the problem, the EMXClient has taken appropriate action to fix it, continue.
        Parameters:
        terminationCode - termination code
        repeatCount - number of tries
        Returns:
        whether to attempt to reestablish the connection

      • updateConversationID

        protected void updateConversationID(int ackType,
                                    int msgType,
                                    String msgRef,
                                    long convID)
        Updates the details of an already sent EMX message with the EMX Conversation ID assigned to it by the Hub. Clients whose applications initiate new EMX conversations (ie they begin a new series of messages by sending an originating OINP or VREQ) should implement this method so that the EMX Conversation ID number that has been assigned by the EMX Hub can be recorded against the originating message.

        Note that the EMX Conversation ID is returned by the Hub in the MACK or MERR that is sent in response to the originating message. Your application is quite entitled to extract the EMX Conversation ID from the MACK or MERR in its handleMACKMessage and handleMERRMessage methods. But you may find it more convenient to use this method, which is called whenever a MACK or MERR is received prior to (and in addition to) the handleMACKMessage or handleMERRMessage method.

        Typically, only applications that send new OINP and/or VREQ messages need to implement this method.

        Parameters:
        ackType - Either MsgTypeMACK or MsgTypeMERR, indicating whether a positive or a negative acknowledgement was received from the Hub.
        msgType - An indicator of the type of the message that the MACK or MERR was in response to. In normal use of this method, this will typically be either MsgTypeOINP or MsgTypeVREQ and can be used to determine whether the msgRef parameter is an Order Reference or a Valuation Reference.
        msgRef - The Original Message Reference returned by the MACK or MERR. This will be the Order Reference or the Valuation Reference of the message your application originally sent. You can look up this message in your application's database (for example) by using this as the key.
        convID - The EMX Conversation ID that the Hub has allocated to the message your application originally sent.

      • handleCertificateNotFound

        protected boolean handleCertificateNotFound(EMXMessage message,
                                            String signerCompID,
                                            String issuerDN,
                                            BigInteger serialNumber)
        Handles the circumstance of not having a certificate that can be used to verify an incoming message. If a subclass implements this method, it will be called any time a message is received that the verification policy indicates must be verified but the verifier finds that it has been signed by a party whose Certificate is not in the truststore.

        If the return value of this method is true, the message will nevertheless be accepted. Otherwise it will be rejected and will not be passed to the application.

        Therefore, if the user wants to return a MERR, or do any processing of a message rejected because of CertificateNotFound, it should be done by implementing this handler.

        Parameters:
        message - an incoming message
        signerCompID - signer compID
        issuerDN - issuer DN
        serialNumber - serial number
        Returns:
        false, unless overridden by an application subclass.

      • handleVerifyFailure

        protected boolean handleVerifyFailure(EMXMessage message,
                                      String signerCompID,
                                      X509Certificate certificate)
        Handles the case where an incoming message has failed verification. If a client implements this method, it will be called any time a message received from EMX has failed the signature validation check using the certificate read from the truststore that matches the IssuerDN and SerialNumber.

        If the return value of this method is true, the message will nevertheless be accepted. Otherwise it will be rejected and will not be passed to the application.

        Therefore, if the user wants to return a MERR, or do any processing of a message rejected because of VerifyFailure, it should be done by implementing this handler.

        Parameters:
        message - an incoming message
        signerCompID - signer compID
        certificate - certificate
        Returns:
        false, unless overridden by a user subclass.
